#: ../../../reference/random/performance.rst:2
msgid "Performance"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/random/performance.rst:7
msgid "Recommendation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/random/performance.rst:9
msgid ""
"The recommended generator for general use is `PCG64` or its upgraded variant "
"`PCG64DXSM` for heavily-parallel use cases. They are statistically high "
"quality, full-featured, and fast on most platforms, but somewhat slow when "
"compiled for 32-bit processes. See :ref:`upgrading-pcg64` for details on "
"when heavy parallelism would indicate using `PCG64DXSM`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/random/performance.rst:15
msgid ""
"`Philox` is fairly slow, but its statistical properties have very high "
"quality, and it is easy to get an assuredly-independent stream by using "
"unique keys. If that is the style you wish to use for parallel streams, or "
"you are porting from another system that uses that style, then `Philox` is "
"your choice."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/random/performance.rst:21
msgid ""
"`SFC64` is statistically high quality and very fast. However, it lacks "
"jumpability. If you are not using that capability and want lots of speed, "
"even on 32-bit processes, this is your choice."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/random/performance.rst:25
msgid ""
"`MT19937` `fails some statistical tests`_ and is not especially fast "
"compared to modern PRNGs. For these reasons, we mostly do not recommend "
"using it on its own, only through the legacy `RandomState` for reproducing "
"old results. That said, it has a very long history as a default in many "
"systems."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/random/performance.rst:34
msgid "Timings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/random/performance.rst:36
msgid ""
"The timings below are the time in ns to produce 1 random value from a "
"specific distribution.  The original `MT19937` generator is much slower "
"since it requires 2 32-bit values to equal the output of the faster "
"generators."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/random/performance.rst:41
msgid "Integer performance has a similar ordering."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/random/performance.rst:43
msgid ""
"The pattern is similar for other, more complex generators. The normal "
"performance of the legacy `RandomState` generator is much lower than the "
"other since it uses the Box-Muller transform rather than the Ziggurat "
"method. The performance gap for Exponentials is also large due to the cost "
"of computing the log function to invert the CDF. The column labeled MT19973 "
"uses the same 32-bit generator as `RandomState` but produces random variates "
"using `Generator`."
msgstr ""

